rpretation truly goes “all the way down,” carnal hermeneutics rejects the opposition of language to sensibility, word to flesh, text to body.In this volume, an impressive array of today’s preeminent philosophers seek to interpret the surplus of meaning that arises from our carnal embodiment, its role in our experience and understanding, and its engagement with the wider world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHermeneutics. 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 4aGender & Sexuality. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh  aInterpretation.  aSensation.  aSenses.  aTouch.  abody.  aembodiment.  aflesh.  ahermeneutics.1 aAlloa, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Edward S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrétien, Jean-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalque, Emmanuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenry, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearney, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKristeva, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacendrick, Karmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMannoussakis, John Panteleimon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarion, Jean-Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran, Dermot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNancy, Jean-Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Byrne, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re